In January she said she would delay her return indefinitely as she  concentrated on finishing high school.
Ross said Capriati was frightened and upset when she was released into his  custody after her arrest.
"She was very angry at herself for exercising such poor judgment and  getting herself into the trouble that she got herself into," he said.
Meanwhile a judge in Litchfield, Connecticut, has issued a re-arrest  warrant for Wineland, who had been due to appear in court to answer charges he  violated parole on a previous drug conviction.
"I want him," Connecticut prosecutor Andrew Wittstein said. "Sooner or  later, we'll see Mr. Wineland back here."
